# The Ternary Operator

The ternary operator is JavaScript's one-line `if/else`. Its syntax is:

```
condition ? valueIfTrue : valueIfFalse
```

It is an **expression** — it produces a value, so you can use it anywhere a value is expected:

```javascript
const age    = 20;
const status = age >= 18 ? "Adult" : "Minor";
console.log(status); // "Adult"
```

Compared to `if/else`:

```javascript
// if/else version — 5 lines
let status;
if (age >= 18) {
    status = "Adult";
} else {
    status = "Minor";
}

// ternary — 1 line, same result
const status = age >= 18 ? "Adult" : "Minor";
```

Use ternary for simple two-outcome assignments. For complex logic, stick with `if/else if/else`.

## The switch Statement

`switch` compares one expression against a fixed list of values. It is cleaner than a long `if/else if` chain when you are matching a single variable against many specific values:

```javascript
const day = "Wednesday";

switch (day) {
    case "Monday":
    case "Tuesday":
    case "Wednesday":
        console.log("Early week");
        break;
    case "Thursday":
    case "Friday":
        console.log("Late week");
        break;
    default:
        console.log("Weekend");
}
```

### Important: the break keyword

Without `break`, execution **falls through** to the next case and runs it too. Always end each case with `break` (or `return` inside a function) unless you intentionally want fall-through.

## Nullish Coalescing Operator ??

```javascript
const input   = null;
const display = input ?? "No value provided";
```

`??` is similar to `||` but only falls back when the left side is `null` or `undefined` — not when it is `0` or `""`. This makes it safer for optional fields that might legitimately be zero.

In the code example below, you will see the ternary operator, a `switch` statement, and `??` used in a plan feature checker.

codeExample.code:
// Plan Feature Checker — ternary, switch, and ??

const userPlan   = "pro";
const userScore  = 87;
const nickname   = null;

// Ternary — simple two-outcome
const accessLevel = userPlan === "bundle" ? "Full" : "Limited";
console.log(`Access: ${accessLevel}`);

// Ternary for inline grade display
const grade = userScore >= 90 ? "A" : userScore >= 80 ? "B" : "C";
console.log(`Grade: ${grade}`);

// switch — match plan to feature list
switch (userPlan) {
    case "bundle":
        console.log("Features: all 4 languages + AI mentor + offline");
        break;
    case "pro":
        console.log("Features: 2 languages + AI mentor");
        break;
    case "starter":
        console.log("Features: 1 language");
        break;
    default:
        console.log("Features: Python only (free tier)");
}

// ?? — nullish coalescing
const displayName = nickname ?? "CodeGuru Learner";
console.log(`Hello, ${displayName}!`);

